Below is a structured 90-Day Microsoft 365 Security Roadmap you can include in your GPT project. It is designed to guide someone from a new or poorly secured tenant → a mature Zero Trust security posture.

This roadmap aligns with guidance from **Microsoft Zero Trust architecture and security baselines used in Microsoft Entra ID, Microsoft Defender for Office 365, Microsoft Defender for Endpoint, Microsoft Intune, and Microsoft Purview.

The philosophy is simple:

Identity → Access → Devices → Email → Data → Monitoring

This mirrors how most real-world Microsoft security deployments succeed.

⸻

Microsoft 365 Security Roadmap

90 Day Implementation Plan

This roadmap assumes:

• A standard Microsoft 365 tenant
• Enterprise licensing (E3/E5 or equivalent)
• A goal of implementing Zero Trust security architecture

⸻

Phase 1

Day 1–7 — Identity Security Foundation

Identity is the single most important security boundary in Microsoft 365.

Objectives

Establish baseline protection for user accounts and administrators.

Tasks

Enable Multi-Factor Authentication for all users

Enable Self-Service Password Reset

Disable Legacy Authentication

Configure Authentication Methods Policy

Allow only secure authentication methods:

• Microsoft Authenticator
• FIDO2 keys
• Windows Hello for Business

Review Global Administrator accounts

Best practice:

• No more than 3–5 global admins

Create two break-glass emergency accounts

Requirements:

• 20+ character passwords
• Excluded from Conditional Access
• No mailbox license
• Monitoring alerts enabled

Review application registrations and service principals

Remove unused or suspicious applications.

⸻

Phase 2

Day 7–14 — Conditional Access Baseline

Conditional Access is the core security enforcement layer.

Objectives

Deploy foundational Conditional Access policies.

Tasks

Create policies in Report-Only mode first.

Deploy these policies:

CA01 — Block Legacy Authentication

CA02 — Require MFA for All Users

CA03 — Require MFA for Admins

CA04 — Require MFA for Guest Users

CA05 — Block High Risk Sign-ins

CA06 — Block High Risk Users

Create Named Locations

Examples:

• Corporate office IPs
• VPN IPs

Verify Conditional Access using sign-in logs.

After validation:

Move policies from Report-Only → Enabled

⸻

Phase 3

Day 14–30 — Email Security

Email is the #1 attack vector in Microsoft 365 environments.

Objectives

Secure Exchange Online and phishing defenses.

Tasks

Enable anti-phishing policies

Enable Safe Links

Enable Safe Attachments

Enable impersonation protection

Enable mailbox intelligence

Configure external email warning banner

Example:

[External Email] Use caution with links or attachments

Block automatic external email forwarding

Configure anti-malware policies

Implement email authentication:

• SPF
• DKIM
• DMARC

Enable user phishing reporting

This allows users to report suspicious emails.

⸻

Phase 4

Day 30–45 — Device Security

Zero Trust requires trusted devices.

Objectives

Ensure devices meet security requirements before accessing Microsoft 365.

Tasks

Deploy Microsoft Intune device enrollment

Configure device compliance policies

Examples:

• BitLocker encryption required
• Antivirus enabled
• Firewall enabled
• OS version minimum requirements

Create Conditional Access policy:

Require compliant devices for Microsoft 365 access

Enable Microsoft Defender for Endpoint

Deploy Endpoint Detection and Response (EDR)

Apply Microsoft security baselines to endpoints.

⸻

Phase 5

Day 45–60 — Privileged Access Security

Administrative access must be heavily controlled.

Objectives

Protect privileged identities.

Tasks

Deploy Privileged Identity Management (PIM)

Enable Just-In-Time admin access

Remove permanent privileged roles where possible.

Require MFA for all administrative roles.

Create Conditional Access policy:

Require phishing-resistant MFA for admins

Require trusted locations for admin access

Implement admin activity auditing

Review privileged access regularly.

⸻

Phase 6

Day 60–75 — Data Protection

Protect corporate data wherever it resides.

Objectives

Implement classification and protection policies.

Tasks

Create Sensitivity Labels

Examples:

• Public
• Internal
• Confidential
• Highly Confidential

Apply labels to:

• Documents
• Emails
• SharePoint files

Deploy Data Loss Prevention (DLP) policies

Protect sensitive data types:

• Credit card numbers
• Social Security numbers
• Financial data

Enable automatic classification.

Restrict external sharing settings.

⸻

Phase 7

Day 75–90 — Monitoring & Threat Detection

Security requires visibility and monitoring.

Objectives

Establish full security monitoring.

Tasks

Enable Unified Audit Logs

Enable Microsoft Defender alerts

Review Identity Protection alerts

Monitor sign-in activity

Configure security alert notifications

Recommended:

Export logs to SIEM

Example:

Security teams commonly integrate with Microsoft Sentinel.

Enable Automated Investigation and Response.

⸻

Expected Outcome After 90 Days

At the end of the roadmap, the tenant should have:

• MFA enforced for all users
• Conditional Access fully implemented
• Legacy authentication disabled
• Secure email protection
• Device compliance enforcement
• Privileged identity protection
• Data classification and protection
• Security monitoring and alerting

This aligns with Microsoft Zero Trust architecture.

